# Implementation Plan: Email & Google Authenticator Integration

We will build a real Node.js backend to handle authentic email sending and Google Authenticator setup.

## User Review Required

> [!CAUTION]
> **Real Email Setup:** To send a real email, we need to use a real SMTP server. I will set up the code to use a Gmail account. You will need to create a `.env` file and provide your own Gmail address and a Gmail "App Password" (which you must generate from your Google Account settings). Without this, the server cannot send actual emails.
> 
> **Authenticator Support:** To use Google Authenticator, a user must first **scan a QR code** the first time they log in or register. I will add a new step to show this QR code immediately after Email Verification.
> 
> Please confirm if you are comfortable providing your own Gmail credentials in a `.env` file (which stays entirely on your local machine) for testing this out.

## Proposed Changes

### Backend Setup
#### [MODIFY] package.json
- Add dependencies: `nodemailer` (for emails), `dotenv` (for loading `.env` variables), `otplib` (for Google Authenticator logic), `qrcode` (for drawing the QR code to scan).

#### [MODIFY] server.js
- Add endpoints: 
  - `POST /api/register` (creates user, sends real email OTP using Nodemailer)
  - `POST /api/verify-email` (verifies email OTP, provisions a TOTP secret via `otplib`, generates QR Code with `qrcode`)
  - `POST /api/login` (checks password, prompts MFA)
  - `POST /api/verify-mfa` (checks the standard 6-digit TOTP code)

#### [NEW] .env.example
- A template file showing how you should configure your email.

---

### Frontend Setup
#### [MODIFY] public/index.html
- Remove the yellow boxes labeled "Simulated Email Code".
- Add a new "MFA Setup" section to display the generated QR Code to the user so they can scan it with their Google Authenticator app.

#### [MODIFY] public/js/app.js
- Replace `localStorage` mock logic with `fetch()` calls pointing to our new Express endpoints.
- Manage tracking the session / JWT returned by the backend.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. Open the `.env` file and fill in actual Gmail credentials.
2. Run `npm start`.
3. Open the app in the browser. Register with a real email account.
4. Check the inbox of that real email account and enter the code.
5. Scan the resulting QR code with the Google Authenticator app on your phone.
6. Check that logging in validates the code perfectly against the phone's live code.
